    <div class="step-instructions screensteps-textblock screensteps-wrapper--introduction screensteps-wrapper">
  <div id="text-content_7d0a735e-1f97-4cf9-bda6-d93ec994d203" class="text-block-content">
    <p>You can embed images in the Rich Content Editor. Image files can be uploaded from your computer or added using a URL. You can also <a href="/t5/Instructor-Guide/How-do-I-embed-images-from-Canvas-into-the-Rich-Content-Editor/ta-p/856" target="_blank">embed images from your course and user files</a>.</p>
<p>Several features in Canvas support the Rich Content Editor, including Announcements, Assignments, Discussions, Pages, Quizzes, and Syllabus.</p>
<p><strong>Notes: </strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Images uploaded from your computer using the image upload tool are added to your <a href="/t5/Instructor-Guide/How-do-I-view-course-files-as-an-instructor/ta-p/713" target="_blank">course files</a>.</li>
<li>You can embed a variety of image file types. Learn what <a href="/t5/Instructor-Guide/What-types-of-media-files-can-I-upload-in-Canvas-as-an/ta-p/1142" target="_blank">types of image files you can embed</a>.</li>
<li>If you are using Usage Rights, you must <a href="/t5/Instructor-Guide/How-do-I-set-usage-rights-and-user-access-for-a-course-file/ta-p/796" target="_blank">set the file usage rights</a> before the file will be accessible to students.</li>
</ul>
  </div>
</div>

    <div class="html-embed">
